      "summary": "Stung by Cupid's arrow, the god Apollo burns with love for the nymph Daphne, who has sworn herself to a virgin life like Diana. He pursues; she flees. At the river's edge, exhausted, she begs her father, the river-god Peneus, to destroy the beauty that has trapped her. He answers by turning her into a laurel tree — and Apollo, denied her, claims the laurel as his sacred emblem forever.",
      "context": "Apollo and Daphne opens the long chain of love-and-transformation stories that give the Metamorphoses its shape. Ovid frames it as a contest of arrows: Apollo has just boasted of killing the serpent Python, and the small god Cupid punishes that arrogance by making the great archer helpless. It is the poem's thesis in miniature — even the gods are not exempt from change, and power over monsters is no power over the heart.",
      "characters": [
        {
          "name": "Apollo",
          "note": "God of the sun, prophecy, music, and the bow. Here he is humbled: the master archer felled by a smaller archer's arrow."
        },
        {
          "name": "Daphne",
          "note": "A nymph, daughter of the river Peneus, devoted to the hunt and to chastity. Her name becomes the Greek word for laurel."
        },
        {
          "name": "Cupid",
          "note": "Roman Eros, god of desire. He fires two arrows — gold to kindle love in Apollo, lead to repel it in Daphne."
        },
        {
          "name": "Peneus",
          "note": "Daphne's father, a Thessalian river-god, who grants her plea by transforming her."
        }
      ],
      "reception": "The chase became one of the most painted and sculpted scenes in Western art — above all Bernini's marble of 1625, which freezes the instant bark climbs Daphne's fingers into leaves. Poets from Petrarch to the Renaissance read the laurel (Latin laurus) as the prize of poetry itself, so that Apollo's loss is recast as the origin of the poet's crown. The myth has since been read as a story about consent and the costs of unwanted pursuit.",
