      "summary": "Imprisoned on Crete, the master craftsman Daedalus builds wings of feathers and wax so he and his son Icarus can escape by air. He warns the boy to fly a middle course. Exhilarated, Icarus climbs toward the sun; the wax melts, the feathers scatter, and he falls into the sea that now bears his name, while his father can only cry out his lost name.",
      "context": "The flight follows Daedalus's earlier ingenuity — the labyrinth he built to hold the Minotaur. Ovid turns the craftsman's triumph into a tragedy of overreach, but pointedly locates the fatal error in youthful joy rather than malice. The 'middle way' is among antiquity's clearest images of moderation, and of the price of ignoring it.",
