      "summary": "When his bride Eurydice dies of a snakebite, the musician Orpheus descends to the underworld and so moves its rulers with his song that they release her — on one condition: he must not look back until both have reached the light. At the threshold, anxious, he turns. She fades into the dark a second time, and he is left to mourn until his own death.",
      "context": "Ovid tells the story as the opening of his tenth book, where it becomes the frame for a chain of songs Orpheus himself sings. Virgil had given an earlier, fuller version in the Georgics. The single forbidden glance is the hinge of the whole myth: art can almost defeat death, but the artist's human doubt undoes the bargain at the last step.",
