      "summary": "Hades carries off Persephone to be queen of the underworld. Her mother Demeter, goddess of the harvest, searches the earth in grief and lets all growth fail, threatening famine. Zeus brokers a return — but because Persephone has eaten pomegranate seeds in the underworld, she must spend part of each year below. Her descent and return become the turning of the seasons.",
      "context": "The Hymn is our oldest full account, and it doubles as a charter for the Eleusinian Mysteries, the most important secret cult of ancient Greece. The myth explains winter and spring, but it is also a profound study of a mother's grief and a daughter's passage into a new life. The pomegranate seed — a small act with permanent consequences — is its quiet engine.",
