      "context": "Ovid opens his sixth book with a story about art that judges its makers. Arachne's tapestry is, pointedly, a catalogue of divine misconduct — the very kind of story Ovid himself is telling — so the myth quietly asks whether the artist who exposes power can survive it. The detail that her weaving was technically perfect makes the punishment about power, not merit.",
