      "summary": "Warned by Circe, Odysseus stops his crew's ears with wax so they cannot hear the Sirens, whose song lures sailors to their deaths. He alone wishes to hear it, so he has himself lashed to the mast, ordering the men not to release him no matter how he pleads. He hears the song, struggles, and survives — the one man to hear the Sirens and live.",
      "context": "The episode comes amid the Odyssey's catalogue of perils between Circe's island and home. What the Sirens offer is not pleasure but knowledge — they promise to sing all that happened at Troy. Odysseus's solution, binding himself in advance against his own future desire, has fascinated philosophers as the original image of committing to a plan while distrusting your later self.",
