      "summary": "To prove his divine parentage, the boy Phaethon asks his father, the sun-god, for a single day driving the sun's chariot across the sky. Bound by an oath, the god reluctantly agrees. Phaethon cannot control the immortal horses; the chariot careers wild, scorching the earth, until Zeus strikes him down with a thunderbolt to save the world. He falls flaming into a river.",
      "context": "Ovid gives Phaethon a sweeping, cinematic treatment at the start of his second book — the sky catching fire, rivers drying, the constellations terrified. It is the great cautionary tale of a child who demands the privileges of a parent's power without the capacity to wield it, and of a father whose love, expressed as an unbreakable promise, destroys his son.",
