      "summary": "The Iliad opens not at the war's start but on a quarrel in its tenth year: forced to surrender a war-prize, Agamemnon seizes Achilles' captive Briseis in compensation. The greatest Greek warrior, dishonored, withdraws from battle — and his rage, the poem's very first word, drives everything that follows, costing countless lives until the death of his friend Patroclus draws him back to the field and his own foretold end.",
      "context": "Homer announces his subject in a single word: mēnis, wrath. The poem is not a chronicle of the whole war but a tight study of one man's anger and its cost over a few weeks. Pope's heroic couplets (1715–20) made Homer an English poet for the eighteenth century and remain the most famous English verse Iliad.",
