      "summary": "Fleeing the ruin of Troy, the hero Aeneas leads a band of survivors westward toward Italy, fated to father the race that becomes Rome. Pursued by Juno's hatred and tested above all by his love for Dido of Carthage — which he must abandon for his mission — he embodies pietas: the binding of self to duty, gods, and country.",
      "context": "Virgil wrote Rome's national epic under Augustus, consciously answering Homer — the first half echoes the Odyssey's wanderings, the second the Iliad's war. But where Achilles is defined by rage, Aeneas is defined by duty, often at the cost of his own happiness. Dryden's 1697 version is the most celebrated English Aeneid.",
